    <section id="when-to-trust">
      <h2>When to Trust Each System</h2>

      <h3>Trust System 1 when:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>You have deep expertise in the domain and clear feedback from past performance</li>
        <li>The situation closely resembles situations you've navigated many times before</li>
        <li>The cost of deliberation exceeds the expected improvement in decision quality</li>
        <li>Speed is essential and the decision is reversible</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Engage System 2 when:</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>The situation is genuinely novel — your intuitions are based on patterns that may not transfer</li>
        <li>The decision involves statistics, probability, or base rates</li>
        <li>You notice strong emotional reactions (these are System 1 signals that may or may not be reliable)</li>
        <li>The stakes are high and the decision is difficult to reverse</li>
        <li>You're evaluating a plan you're emotionally invested in</li>
        <li>The problem requires comparing multiple options across multiple dimensions</li>
      </ul>

      <ContentBox type="insight">
        <h3>The Expert Intuition Condition</h3>
        <p>Kahneman, in collaboration with Gary Klein (who studied expert decision-making), concluded that expert intuition is trustworthy when two conditions are met: (1) the domain offers sufficient regularity to learn from — consistent patterns exist to encode; and (2) the expert has received clear, timely feedback over many repetitions. Intuitions formed without these conditions — in domains like political prediction, stock selection, or clinical psychology without rigorous feedback mechanisms — are not reliably better than chance.</p>
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

    <section id="how-to-apply">
      <h2>How to Apply Dual-Process Thinking</h2>
      <StepsList steps={[
        {
          title: "Audit your high-stakes decisions for System 1 override",
          description: "Before committing to any significant decision, pause and ask: Is my confidence here based on genuine expertise with clear feedback, or am I pattern-matching on a situation that only resembles past experience? If the latter, treat your System 1 judgment as a hypothesis to test, not a conclusion to act on."
        },
        {
          title: "Use checklists to activate System 2",
          description: "Checklists are external System 2 activators. By forcing explicit verification of criteria that System 1 might skip (because they feel obvious), checklists catch the predictable errors that automatic processing misses. Surgeons, pilots, and nuclear plant operators use them not because they lack expertise but because expert System 1 thinking can confidently skip steps in familiar-looking situations that are actually different."
        },
        {
          title: "Notice and name your cognitive biases as they occur",
          description: "Kahneman is explicit that awareness of biases does not eliminate them — System 1 continues operating the same way. But naming a bias as it occurs ('I notice I'm anchored to the first number I heard') activates System 2 to recheck the reasoning. This is not a cure, but it is a meaningful upgrade in calibration."
        },
        {
          title: "Seek the outside view for planning decisions",
          description: "Whenever you're planning a project or predicting an outcome, ask: What is the base rate for how similar projects or predictions have actually turned out? This forces the outside view rather than the inside view — reference class forecasting rather than narrative construction. It is the single most reliable correction for planning fallacy."
        },
        {
          title: "Slow down before high-stakes irreversible decisions",
          description: "The default is to endorse System 1's confident outputs. Override this default by building in deliberate delays — sleep on major decisions, write out your reasoning before deciding, explicitly ask 'what would have to be true for the opposite choice to be correct?' These interventions create space for System 2 to examine what System 1 has already judged."
        },
        {
          title: "Build feedback loops for your intuitions",
          description: "Track your System 1 predictions: write down your gut calls and then check outcomes. Over time, you'll learn which domains your intuitions are reliable in and which they aren't. This calibration — knowing when to trust yourself — is the practical output of understanding dual-process theory."
        }
      ]} />
    </section>

    <section id="misconceptions">
      <h2>Common Misconceptions</h2>

      <ContentBox type="warning">
        <h3>❌ "System 2 is always better than System 1"</h3>
        <p>System 2 can be wrong, manipulated, and slower without being more accurate. Deliberate analysis fails when the underlying model is wrong, when it's based on the same biased information System 1 used, or when the analyst is fatigued or motivated to reach a particular conclusion. Expert intuition in high-feedback domains routinely outperforms deliberate novice analysis. The goal is not to always use System 2 but to know when System 1's outputs should be examined.</p>
      </ContentBox>

      <ContentBox type="warning">
        <h3>❌ "Smart people are less susceptible to System 1 errors"</h3>
        <p>Intelligence does not protect against cognitive biases. Kahneman's research, and subsequent replications, show that the same anchoring effects, availability errors, and representativeness failures appear in highly intelligent populations. What higher intelligence does is make people better at rationalizing System 1's outputs after the fact — which can actually increase confidence in biased conclusions. Intellectual sophistication is not cognitive bias immunity.</p>
      </ContentBox>

      <ContentBox type="warning">
        <h3>❌ "You can train yourself out of these biases"</h3>
        <p>Knowing about a bias and eliminating it are different things. System 1 continues to generate the same outputs regardless of your knowledge of behavioral economics. What you can train is the habit of engaging System 2 at the right moments — catching the output of System 1 before committing to it in high-stakes domains. The biases themselves persist; the question is whether they get corrected before becoming decisions.</p>
      </ContentBox>
    </section>

